<section>
<title>Functional Limits</title>

<<<<<<< HEAD
<p>In Calculus 1, we learn about the concepts of <term>continuity of a function</term> and <term>differentiability of a function</term>.  Both these concepts require the use of functional limits.

<md>
<mrow>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x) = L</mrow>
<mrow>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x) = f(c)</mrow>
<mrow>f'(x) = \displaystyle \lim_{h \rightarrow 0} \frac{1}{h} (f(x+h)-f(x))</mrow>
</md>

</p>

<p workspace="3in">The central idea of a functional limit is this:

<md>
<mrow>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x) = L</mrow>
</md>
</p>

<definition xml:id="def-limit">
  <title>Functional Limit</title>
  <statement>
    <p>
      Let <m>f:A \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> and let <m>c</m> be a limit point of the domain <m>A</m>.  We say that <m>\lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x)=L</m> provided that, for all <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>,there exists a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> such that whenever <m>0 &lt; |x-c| &lt; \delta</m> (and <m>x \in A</m>) it follows that <m>|f(x)-L| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
</definition>

</section>
