<section>
<title>Sequential Criterion</title>

<theorem xml:id="thm-lim-seqcrit">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Given a function <m>f: A \rightarrow \mathbb{R}</m> and a limit point <m>c \in A</m>, the following two statements are equivalent:
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x)=L</m>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            For all sequences <m>(x_n) \subset A</m> satisfying <m>x_n \neq c</m> and <m>(x_n) \rightarrow c</m>, it follows that <m>f(x_n) \rightarrow L</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </p>
  </statement>
</theorem>

<p workspace="2in"></p>

<proof>
  <p>
    (<m>\Rightarrow</m>) Suppose the first statement is true.  We must show that given any sequence <m>(x_n) \subset A</m> satisfying <m>x_n \neq c</m> we can conclude that <m>f(x_n) \rightarrow L</m>.  This means, given an <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m>, we want to be able find an <m>N=N(\epsilon)</m> for which <m>n &gt; N</m> implies <m>|f(x_n)-L| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Let <m>(x_n) \subset A</m> be a sequence satisfying <m>x_n \neq c</m>.  And let <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> be given.  Since <m>\lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x)=L</m>, we know there is a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> for which <m>0 &lt; |x-c| &lt; \delta</m> implies that <m>|f(x)-L| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    We invoke the definition of sequential convergence of <m>(x_n)</m> with <m>\delta &gt; 0</m>.  There is an <m>N_1=N_1(\delta)</m> for which <m>n &gt; N</m> means <m>|x_n-c| &lt; \delta</m>.  This lets us invoke the given (1) to conclude that <m>|f(x_n)-L| &lt; \epsilon</m>, as desired.
  </p>
  <p>
    (<m>\Leftarrow</m>). Suppose that the second statement is true.  We must show that, given any <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> we can find a <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> for which <m>|x-c| &lt; \delta</m> implies <m>|f(x)-L| &lt; \epsilon</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    The book proves the contrapositive by contradiction!  That is, it proves that if (1) is false then (2) is false by assuming (1) is false and (2) is true, arriving at a contradiction.  Here's how that goes.
  </p>
  <p>
    Suppose (2) is true.  For (1) to be false means there is at least one <m>\epsilon_0 &gt; 0</m> for which no <m>\delta &gt; 0</m> gets <m>x</m> close enough to <m>c</m> to guarantee <m>|f(x)-L| &lt; \epsilon_0</m>.  This means there will always be at least one input <m>x_*</m> with <m>|x_*-c| &lt; \delta</m> and with <m>|f(x_*)-L| &gt; \epsilon_0</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Consider <m>\delta_n=1/n</m>.  For each <m>n</m>, let <m>x_n</m> be the input with <m>|x_n-c| &lt; \delta</m> and with <m>|f(x_n)-L| &gt; \epsilon_0</m>.  This gives us a sequence <m>(x_n)</m> that converges to <m>c</m> at the same time that the sequence <m>(f(x_n))</m> does not converge to <m>L</m>.  But this contradicts (2), which we took to be true.  Therefore, (1) cannot be false at the same time (2) is true.  Therefore (2) must be false.  We conclude that (2) implies (1).  
  </p>
</proof>
</section>

<!-- ============================ -->

<section>
  <title>Useful Corollaries</title>

  <corollary xml:id="cor-alglimthmfcn">
    <title>Algebraic Limit Theorem for Functional Limits</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> and <m>g</m> be functions defined on a domain <m>A \subset \mathbb{R}</m>, and assume <m>\lim_{x \rightarrow c}f(x)=L</m> and <m>\lim_{x \rightarrow c}g(x)=M</m> for some limit point <m>c</m> of <m>A</m>.  Then
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow c} kf(x) = kL</m> for all <m>k \in \mathbb{R}</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow c} (f(x)+g(x)) = L+M</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x)g(x) = LM</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>\displaystyle \lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x)/g(x) = L/M</m>, provided <m>M \neq 0</m>
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </p>
    </statement>
  </corollary>

  <corollary xml:id="cor-divcrit">
    <title>Divergence Criterion for Functional Limits</title>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>f</m> be a function defined on <m>A \subset \mathbb{R}</m>, and let <m>c</m> be a limit point of <m>A</m>.  If there exists two sequences <m>(x_n)</m> and <m>(y_n)</m> in <m>A</m> with <m>x_n \neq c</m> and <m>y_n \neq c</m> and
        <md>
          <mrow> \lim x_n \amp = \lim y_n =c</mrow>
        </md>
        but
        <md>
          <mrow>\lim f(x_n) \amp \neq  \lim f(y_n) </mrow>
        </md>
        then we can conclude that the function limit <m>\lim_{x \rightarrow c} f(x)</m> does not exist.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </corollary>


=======
  <proof>
  <p>
    Without loss of generality, we can assume that <m>x_i &lt; x_{i+1}</m> for <m>1=1,2,3,\ldots,N-1</m>.  Then
    <md>
      <mrow> x_1 -1 \amp &lt; x &lt; x_n+1 </mrow>
    </md>
    so <m>K</m> is bounded by <m>\max\{|x_1-1|,x_{n}+1|\}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    To show that <m>K</m> is closed we argue indirectly.  Suppose <m>(y_k) \subset K</m> is a Cauchy sequence with limit <m>y</m>.  This means that <m>y</m> is a limit point of <m>K</m>.  We need to show <m>y \in K</m>.
  </p>
  <p workspace="2in">
    Suppose not.  Suppose <m>y \notin K</m>.  Then <m>|x-y| &gt; 0</m> for all <m>x \in K</m>.  (The inequality equals zero precisely when <m>x=y</m>.). Define
    <md>
      <mrow>\mathcal{O}_x \amp =\{u \in K \, : \, |u-x| &lt; \frac{1}{2}|x-y|\}</mrow>
    </md>
  </p>
  <p>The closer <m>x</m> is to <m>y</m>, the smaller the radius of <m>\mathcal{O}_x</m>.  The collection <m>\{\mathcal{O}_x\}_{x \in K}</m> is an open cover of <m>K</m>.  By the Heine-Borel property, this open cover has a finite subcover, <m>\{\mathcal{O}_{x_i}\}_{i=1}^{n}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Consider <m>\epsilon_0 = \min\{\frac{1}{2}|x_i-y|\}</m>, which is the smallest radius of the open sets in our finite subcover.  Since <m>(y_n) \rightarrow y</m>, there is an <m>N &gt; 0</m> such that <m>|y-n-y| &lt; \epsilon_0</m> for <m>n &gt; N</m>.  But these <m>y_n</m> are outside every <m>\mathcal{O}_{x_i}</m>.  So out purported finite subcover does not cover <m>K</m>!  This is a contradicion.
  </p>
  <p>
    Consequently, <m>K</m> is compact.
  </p>
  </proof>


</section>

<section>
  <title>The Heine-Borel Property</title>
  
  <example>
    <title>The singleton set has the Heine-Borel property</title>
        
  <p>
    Let <m>x \in \mathbb{R}</m> and consider <m>F=\{x\}</m>, the singleton set.
  </p>
  <p>
    What would an open cover of <m>F</m> look like.  Consider <m>I=(a,b)</m> where <m>a &lt; x &lt; b b</m>.  Then <m>x \in I</m>.  The collection <m>\mathcal{U}=\{I\}</m> is an open cover of <m>F</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Suppose <m>\mathcal{U}=\{U_{\lambda}\,:\, \lambda \in \Lambda \}</m> is an open cover of <m>F</m>.   This means
    <md>
      <mrow>F \amp \subset \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} U_{\lambda}.</mrow>
    </md>
    So <m>x \in U_{\lambda_0}</m> for some <m>\lambda_0 \in \Lambda</m>.  Let's define <m>\mathcal{U}_0 = \{ U_{\lambda_0}\}</m>.  Then <m>\mathcal{U}_0 \subset \mathcal{U}</m> is a subset of our open cover of <m>F</m>.  And because <m>\mathcal{U}_0</m> is a finite collection, it is a finite subcover of <m>\mathcal{U}</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    Note that we've just proved that <m>F=\{x\}</m> has the Heine-Borel property.  That is to say, <m>\{x\}</m> is a compact set.
  </p>  
  </example>
  
  <example>
    <title>A finite set has the Heine-Borel property</title>
        
  <p>
    Let <m>x_i \in \mathbb{R}</m> and consider <m>F=\{x_1,x_2,x_3,\ldots,x_n\}</m>.  Suppose <m>\mathcal{U}=\{U_{\lambda}\,:\, \lambda \in \Lambda \}</m> is an open cover of <m>F</m>.   This means
    <md>
      <mrow>F \amp \subset \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} U_{\lambda}.</mrow>
    </md>
    Let's see how to extract a finite subcover of <m>F</m> from <m>\mathcal{U}</m>.  Take <m>x_1 \in F</m>.  Since <m>\mathcal{U}</m> is an open cover of <m>F</m>, <m>x_1 \in \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} U_{\lambda}</m>.  This means <m>x_1 \in U_{\lambda_1}</m> for some <m>\lambda_1 \in \Lambda</m>.  Set this open set aside for our finite subcover, then consider <m>x_2 \in \bigcup_{\lambda \in \Lambda} U_{\lambda}</m>.  This means <m>x_2 \in U_{\lambda_2}</m> for some <m>\lambda_2 \in \Lambda</m>.  Add this set to our collection of open set, then repeat this process for each <m>x_k</m> that remains to find <m>U_{\lambda_k}</m> containing <m>x_k</m>.  When we exhaust the numbers in <m>F</m>, we end up with a collection of at most <m>n</m> open sets <m>\{ U_{\lambda_k} \, : \, 1 \leq k \leq n\}</m>.  This is a finite subcover of <m>F</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    This proves that <m>F</m> has the Heine-Borel property.  That is to say, <m>\{x_1, x_2, x_3, \ldots, x_n\}</m> is a compact set.
  </p>
  </example>

<example>
    <title>The open interval <m>(0,1)</m> does not have the Heine-Borel property</title>
        
  <p>
    Let <m>\mathcal{O}=(0,1)</m>.  Let 
    <md>
      <mrow>
        \mathcal{U} \amp =\{ (\epsilon,1) \subset \mathbb{R} \, : \, 0 &lt; \epsilon &lt; 1\}
      </mrow>
    </md>
  This is an open cover of <m>\mathcal{O}</m> because given any <m>x \in \mathcal{O}</m>, there is an <m>\epsilon &gt; 0</m> with <m>0 &lt; \epsilon &lt; x</m>.  Thus <m>x \in (\epsilon,1)</m>, an open set in the collection <m>\mathcal{U}</m>.  
  </p>
  <p>
    If <m>\mathcal{O}</m> had the Heine-Borel property, <m>\mathcal{U}</m> would have a finite subcover, <m>\mathcal{U}_0</m>.  But then the intervals in the subcover would have a smallest left endpoint, <m>\epsilon_0 &gt; 0</m>.  By the Archimedean Property of the reals, this leaves real numbers between 0 and <m>\epsilon_0</m> uncovered!  Thus <m>\mathcal{U}_0</m> could not be a cover of <m>(0,1)</m>.
  </p>
  <p>
    This shows that <m>\mathcal{O}</m> does not have the Heine-Borel property.  That is to say, <m>\mathcal{O}</m> is not compact.
  </p>
  </example>
